Background

From the iPod to the iPhone and Mac lineups, Apple has always pushed the boundaries in technology and design. After its move from PowerPC to Intel chips Apple has enjoyed a series of iMac and MacBook Pro lineups that have helped to shape industry and make a big impact on professionals, artists, cinematographers, musicians, developers, etc. Now that Apple is making a big push to Apple Silicon in its Mac lineup lets take a look back on their technology with Intel and now with the addition of the new Apple Silicon M1 Chip:

  1. Does CPU Geekbench scores play an impact into the pricing of Apples iMac and MacBook lineup?

In this analysis, data has been gathered from a lineup of todays and previous iMac and MacBook computers. The data that a Multiple Linear Regression will be performed on and analyzed will be displayed at the bottom of this analysis.

Hypothesis

This analysis attempts to model the price of Apple iMacs and Apple MacBook Pros according to their reported Geekbench scores (based off of multi-threading) using a multiple linear regression. Specifically,

\[ \underbrace{Y_i}_{\text{Price}} = \overbrace{\beta_0 + \beta_1 \underbrace{X_{i1}}_{\text{Mileage}}}^{\text{iMac}} + \overbrace{\beta_2 \underbrace{X_{i2}}_{\text{1 if MacBook}} + \beta_3 \underbrace{X_{i1} X_{i2}}_{\text{Interaction}}}^{\text{MacBook Adjustments to Line}} + \epsilon_i \]

where \(\epsilon\)\(_i\) N(0,\(\sigma\)2) and X\(_i\)\(_2\) = 0 when the computer is an iMac and X\(_i\)\(_2\) = 1 when the vehicle is a MacBook. This forced 0, 1 encoding for X\(_i\)\(_2\) produces the following models.

Vehicle Value of X\(_i\)\(_2\) Resulting Model
iMac X\(_i\)\(_2\) = 0 Y\(_i\) = \(\beta\)\(_0\) + \(\beta\)\(_1\) X\(_i1\) + \(\epsilon\)\(_i\)
MacBook X\(_i\)\(_2\) = 1 Y\(_i\) = (\(\beta\)\(_0\) + \(\beta\)\(_2\)) + (\(\beta\)\(_1\) + \(\beta\)\(_3\))X\(_i\)\(_1\) + \(\epsilon\)\(_i\)
\[ H_0: \beta_1 = 0 \] \[ H_a: \beta_1 \neq 0 \] \(\alpha\) = 0.05

Showing these separated models for each computer demonstrates that \(\beta\)\(_2\) is the difference between the y-intercepts for the iMac and MacBook. The difference in the slopes for the two models is also demonstrated by \(\beta\)\(_3\).

We can assume that the average cost (y-intercept) of these computers is greater than zero and the computers increase with higher GeekBench Scores. So there will be no need to test the coefficients of \(\beta\)\(_0\) or \(\beta\)\(_1\) for any differences from zero. These are the baseline intercept and slope for the iMac computers, and we will assume they are different from zero. The point of interest here is whether the regression lines for the iMac and MacBook have different y-intercepts and different slopes.

A scatterplot of the relationship between price and Geekbench scores shows a strong positive trend. The dots are somewhat clustered around the bottom-left corner and seem to be a good fit as the line progresses.

# FULL MODEL
mylm <- lm(Price ~ CPUmulti_Scores + Type + CPUmulti_Scores:Type, data=Computers)
#summary(cars.lm)

b <- mylm$coefficients

palette(c("gray25","#86CA48"))

plot(Price ~ CPUmulti_Scores, data=Computers, col=as.factor(Type), pch=16, main="iMac vs. MacBook", ylab="Price ($)", xlab="Geekbench Scores")

abline(b[1],b[2], col="gray25")
abline((b[1]+b[3]), (b[2]+b[4]), col = "#86CA48")

legend("topright", col=palette(), pch=21, legend=c("iMac", "MacBook"), bty="n", text.col = palette())

The estimated average slope of the iMac regression is 0.7663, which is significantly different from zero (p = 1.182e-09) meaning the relationship is meaningful as well as the slope for the MacBook Pro (p = 0.01332). The following is a complete table showing the summary of the full regression results.

Intepretation

Assuming the model is appropriate, then we can estimate that an increase in a Geekbench score by about 2000 will result in around an extra $1,800 in price on average. Judging from the estimated value of 0.766, it shows that the average price of iMac computers is 76.63% of the reported Geekbench scores. For the MacBook Pro a jump from a GeekBench score of 4000 to 6000 is about an average $397.04 in price. From a technological perspective this seems to be almost correct of todays technology considering that new and high performing technology tend to have high prices. But with the addition of the new Apple M1 chip there seems to be an outlier since the M1 chip is unlike the Intel Chips for MacBook. The MacBook Pro with the new M1 Chip has the highest GeekBench score out of all the MacBook Pros and comes at a price of $1299! This is definitely a new market disturber and perhaps opens up the field to a new type of up and coming computers. The only reason I can suppose that this particular MacBook Pro is cheaper is because Apple no longer has to charge more due to the Intel Chips being extremely expensive and having low GeekBench performance scores.

Thus in answer to the stated questionsassuming the model appropriateis that Apple Silicons have a higher price with a higher performance as made by Apple in their WWDC 2020 Apple Developer Conference. With a higher performance, Geekbench scores will most definitely be higher thus playing a major impact in the pricing of Apples iMac and MacBook lineup. This is only the beginning so we will have to see further impact of the new M1 chip and the new Apple Silicon chips to come.

Appropriateness of the above Regression

A check on the appropriateness of the model shows some question only on the part of the Q-Q Plot. The Q-Q plot seems to show slight irregularity (possible heavy-tailed granted there is more data points) on the ends. From these violations to Assumption #2 of the five assumptions, it is safe to assume that the regression is not as trustworthy. The plots below demonstrate this difficulty.

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(mylm,which=1:2)
plot(mylm$residuals)
